var _frontmatter = {
  "templateKey": "content-pages",
  "title": "How do writers respond to audience expectations?",
  "key": "how-do-writers-respond-to-audience-expectations",
  "parentKey": "how-is-writing-a-social-activity",
  "points": [{
    "point": "Meeting the needs and expectations of audiences gives writing more impact, but sometimes it is difficult to know what audiences expect.\n\n**FOR INSTRUCTORS**: Student writers will face many choices in engaging with their audiences. \n\n[In thinking about their audiences, some students might shift between different kinds of academic and non-academic writing.](https://hdl.handle.net/2027/fulcrum.10079890/poi.25) \n\nFor example, as [Lizzie Hutton and Gail Gibson found](https://hdl.handle.net/2027/fulcrum.10079890/poi.25), \"students who align their writing development with the 'academic' tend to see writing as constituting the communication of thought\" (90).\n\nIn other words, some students prefer to write in ways that match the writing of a particular style or discipline (e.g., science).\n\nOn the other hand, \"students who talked about their growth as writers as more closely tied to the 'creative' tend to understand writing instead as constituting the generation of thought\" (90). \n\nIn this case, some students prefer to write in a way that creates new ideas.\n\nUsing different kinds of writing helps us reach audiences in different ways.\n\nAsking students to write about who their audience is and how they are reaching them can help them align their writing with readers they envision.\n\nAs [Ryan McCarty’s chapter shows, students’ experiences and perspectives of their roles as writers and their writing influence the way they see their audiences.](https://hdl.handle.net/2027/fulcrum.10079890/poi.30) \n\n> [I think more of a development, because it was a different form of writing. It also helped me reflect upon the way we write in science. Between the two, it showed me how I can communicate effectively when we do talk about—okay, so you’re talking to more of a lay audience as opposed to the scientific community in communicating your research. Let’s look at different ways to read and write.](https://hdl.handle.net/2027/fulcrum.10079890/poi.30)",
    "title": "What are our audiences’ expectations?"
  }, {
    "point": "Writing **to** others means communicating ideas to a specific person or a specific group of people.\n\nAs Anne Gere’s chapter shows, Stephanie reflects on how she uses writing as a trade credit underwriter to speak to her readers.\n\n:::md-component ExpandableBlockquote previewText=\"Now%20I%20am%20doing%20more%20analytical%2C%20a%20lot%20of%20persuasive%20writing%20%u2026\" fullText=\"%5BHere%u2019s%20what%20I%20recommend.%20Here%20are%20seven%20or%20eight%20bullet%20points%20of%20financial%20ratios%20%20and%20%20positive%20or%20negative%20news%20and%20press%20releases.%20Here%u2019s%20%20how%20the%20soybean%20crop%20is%20going%20in%20Brazil%20and%20all%20that%u2026%20diplomatic%20emails%20to%20%20brokers%2C%20the%20people%20who%20stand%20between%20us%20and%20our%20clients%2C%20trying%20to%20sugarcoat%20the%20no%u2019s%20and%20make%20the%20yes%u2019s%20kind%20of%20sound%20like%20we%u2019re%20doing%20them%20a%20favor.%5D%28https%3A//hdl.handle.net/2027/fulcrum.10079890/poi.37%29\"\n\nWriting **for** others can mean making communication accessible to as many readers as possible.\n\nLet’s consider Dan, who uses social media to reach out to his audience.\n\n:::md-component ExpandableBlockquote previewText=\"I%20am%20seeing%20a%20lot%20of%20upcoming%20writers%20or%20a%20lot%20of%20upcoming%20students%20%u2026\" fullText=\"%5Bbecause%20they%u2019re%20interacting%20with%20me%20on%20Twitter%20on%20an%20everyday%20basis%20or%20on%20Facebook%u2026%20Social%20media%u2014I%20like%20to%20think%20of%20it%20as%20talking%20from%20a%20position%20of%20power.%20You%20can%20say%2C%20%u2018Why%20don%u2019t%20you%20look%20at%u2026%5D%28https%3A//hdl.handle.net/2027/fulcrum.10079890/poi.38%29\"\n\nWhen we write __to__ our audiences, we call their attention in some way, and when we write __for__ our audiences, we invite them into our writing. In either case, we are thinking about different ways of engaging with them.",
    "title": "Are we writing to or for audiences?"
  }, {
    "point": "Reaching audiences can depend a lot on kinds of writing and purpose.\n\nOne challenge is knowing which kinds of writing are appropriate for the audiences being addressed.\n\nConsider Kris, who finds the language of science to be a necessary step in her development as a writer.\n\n:::md-component ExpandableBlockquote previewText=\"At%20first%20when%20I%20was%20starting%20to%20read%20papers%20...\" fullText=\"%5BAt%20first%20when%20I%20was%20starting%20to%20read%20papers%20I%20thought%20scientists%20used%20unnecessarily%20large%20words%20to%20describe%20things.%20Then%20what%20I%20found%20as%20I%20started%20writing%20was%20that%20we%20have%20a%20specific%20vocabulary%2C%20just%20like%20any%20field%20does%2C%20and%20it%u2019s%20just%20way%20easier%20to%20communicate%20in%20that%20way.%20You%20can%20use%20one%20word%20to%20describe%20what%20would%20have%20to%20be%20used%20as%20a%20whole%20sentence.%5D%28https%3A//hdl.handle.net/2027/fulcrum.10079890/poi.29%29\"\n\nAnother challenge is making sure purposes for writing are clear to audiences.\n\nConsider Kaitlin, who explores how her [multimodal purposes](/pages/writing-involves-choices/how-do-we-write-in-the-digital-age/what-is-multimodal-composition-and-where-do-people-encounter-it/#what-counts-as-multimodal-composition) affect how her audiences think about traveling.\n\n:::md-component ExpandableBlockquote previewText=\"I%20would%20pick%20out%20quotes%20where%20it%20was%20making%20the%20point%20that%20I%20wanted%20...\" fullText=\"%5BI%20would%20pick%20out%20quotes%20where%20it%20was%20making%20the%20point%20that%20I%20wanted%20but%20over%20an%20image%2C%20so%20you%u2019re%20not%20just%20immediately%20assaulted%20with%20a%20ton%20of%20text.%20You%20have%20%20to%20%20scroll%20%20over%20%20it%20%20to%20%20see%20%20it%u2026%20%u2018Why%20do%20people%20adventure%2C%20and%20what%20do%20they%20know%20that%20I%20don%u2019t%3F%5D%28https%3A//hdl.handle.net/2027/fulcrum.10079890/poi.35%29\"\n\nAnd so, we make our writing matter for our audiences by making choices about style and delivery.\n\n[One way we can determine how well our writing is addressing our audiences is by having other people take a look at it.](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1KBpTwBrxv_NuFW9xCcvWBDIlUMQ-IrSnp-8T-U0Lpi8/edit#bookmark=id.6qky7jevpdp0)",
    "title": "How can we make writing matter for audiences?"
  }, {
    "point": "Writers make important decisions about what to write and for whom. Click on the options below to see relationships between writing situations and writers: identities, the topic, and who the readers are.\n\n<Activity>",
    "title": "Putting it all together"
  }],
  "afterPoints": "Good writers think about their audiences’ needs and expectations, including how choices they make can meet those needs and expectations."
};

